entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 16 at 4:36AM AKDT by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
An arctic front will move across the Interior today, which will usher in blustery westerly winds and accumulating snow showers, with wind gusts into the 25 to 35 mph range. Snow accumulations will also impact the morning commute, so residents are advised to leave plenty of time. High pressure will then settle over the region Friday morning through Sunday morning, which will result in morning low temperatures falling across the Interior to well below seasonal normals. This will represent the coldest temps of the season thus far, with lower elevation valley locations dropping into the single digits, with a 20 percent chance of below zero temps across the typical very cold valley locations by Saturday morning. Residents are advised to make proper cold weather preparations in advance.
Attention turns to a developing winter storm which is currently projected to impact the Interior late Sunday night/early Monday morning and lasting into the middle of next week. Significant accumulations of snowfall are possible across a wide swath of the Interior, as the southwest flow pattern will have plenty of moist air from the Bering Sea to work with. Mixed rain/snow is also possible during this storm event, so disruptions to travel are likely early next week.

entry.title: Red Flag Warning issued October 16 at 5:30AM PDT until October 19 at 5:00PM PDT by NWS San Francisco CA
entry.summary:
...RED FLAG WARNING NOW IN EFFECT THURSDAY NIGHT THROUGH SATURDAY EVENING FOR THE BAY AREA AND CENTRAL COAST AS STRONG OFFSHORE WINDS AND CRITICALLY DRY CONDITIONS ARE EXPECTED TO DEVELOP...
.Gusty north-northeast winds are expected to develop as an "inside slider" system moves into the Great Basin this weekend. Humidities will still be on the higher end at the start of the event on Thursday, but are expected to quickly dry out as low as 10% Friday and Saturday. Peak winds are expected overnight Thursday night into Friday morning for the North Bay and Bay Area. Most areas across the region will be affected to some degree, with likely exceptions being the immediate Big Sur coast, Monterey Bay coast, and the Marin/Sonoma coast. Winds largely on the order of 25-35 mph can be expected with gusts to 50 mph... isolated gusts to 65 mph across the highest terrain and ridgetops, most notably the North Bay Interior Mountains and the Diablo Range.
* AFFECTED AREA...Fire Weather Zone 006 San Francisco, Fire Weather Zone 502 Marin Coastal Range, Fire Weather Zone 503 Sonoma Coastal Range, Fire Weather Zone 504 North Bay Interior Mountains, Fire Weather Zone 506 North Bay Interior Valleys, Fire Weather Zone 508 San Francisco Bay Shoreline, Fire Weather Zone 509 San Francisco Peninsula Coast, Fire Weather Zone 510 East Bay Interior Valleys, Fire Weather Zone 512 Santa Cruz Mountains, Fire Weather Zone 513 Santa Clara Valley Including San Jose, Fire Weather Zone 514 Eastern Santa Clara Hills and Fire Weather Zone 515 East Bay Hills.
* TIMING...11 PM Thursday until 5 PM Saturday
* WINDS...North 25 to 35 mph with gusts up to 50 mph.
* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...As low as 12 percent.
* LIGHTNING...None.
* IMPACTS...The combination of gusty winds and low humidity can cause fire to rapidly grow in size and intensity. Outdoor burning is not recommended. Despite recent cool weather and high humidity, we are expecting a widespread and prolonged offshore wind event which will likely dry fuels out very quickly given their volatility over the past several weeks.

entry.title: Red Flag Warning issued October 16 at 6:52AM CDT until October 16 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Bismarck ND
entry.summary:
...RED FLAG WARNING FOR PORTIONS OF SOUTH CENTRAL AND SOUTHEAST NORTH DAKOTA THIS AFTERNOON AND EARLY EVENING...
.Warm and dry conditions with gusty south winds are expected this afternoon into the early evening. The strongest winds are expected from far south central to southeastern North Dakota, with sustained speeds around 25 mph and gusts as high as 40 mph. Minimum humidity will fall as low as 20 percent in these same areas this afternoon. The combination of strong winds and low humidity will produce critical fire weather conditions this afternoon and early evening. Some areas within the Red Flag Warning could see a continuation of at least near-critical fire weather conditions through tonight as southerly winds persist around 20 mph and overnight humidity rises no higher than 40 percent. More widespread critical fire weather conditions could then return to the southern James River Valley and adjacent areas to the west Thursday afternoon.
* WINDS...South around 25 mph with gusts up to 40 mph.
* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...As low as 20 percent.
* AFFECTED AREA...Sioux, Emmons, Logan, McIntosh, LaMoure, and Dickey counties.
* IMPACTS...Any fires that ignite will spread rapidly and become difficult to control or suppress.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 15 at 5:55AM AKDT by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
An arctic front will move across the Interior Wednesday, which will usher in blustery westerly winds and snow showers, with wind gusts across the higher terrain into the 35 mph range. High pressure will then settle over the region Friday morning through Sunday, which will result in low temperatures falling across the Interior to well below seasonal normals. This will represent the coldest temps of the season thus far, with lower elevation valley locations dropping into the single digits, with a 20 percent chance of below zero temps across the typical very cold valley locations by Saturday morning. Residents are advised to make proper cold weather preparations in advance.
For those curious, the climate normals this time of year are rapidly tumbling down. The daily average low for Fairbanks, for instance, drops from 20 degrees October 15th (Tuesday) down to 16 degrees on October 20th. By the end of the month, the average low will be 6 degrees. So far, the lowest temperature at Fairbanks International has been 22 degrees.
